h3. +Issue description+

In some cases, it is possible to delete all the fields from a Request Type (including the Summary field). When this situation happens:
 - the log analyzer returns the following error:
{code:java}
Loading Requests with Anonymous Comments in the Customer Portal fails with 500 error NullPointerException
{code}

 - the following error can be found in the JIRA logs (please note that some text has been replaced with XXXXX for confidentiality purpose):
{code:java}
2017-12-05 09:08:00,541 XXXXXXXXXX ERROR XXXXXXX XXXXXXX XXXXXX XXXXXXXX /rest/servicedesk/1/customer/models [c.a.p.r.c.error.jersey.ThrowableExceptionMapper] Uncaught exception thrown by REST service: key not found: 114
java.util.NoSuchElementException: key not found: 20
	at scala.collection.MapLike$class.default(MapLike.scala:228)
	at scala.collection.AbstractMap.default(Map.scala:59)
	at scala.collection.MapLike$class.apply(MapLike.scala:141)
	at scala.collection.AbstractMap.apply(Map.scala:59)
	at com.atlassian.servicedesk.internal.feature.customer.request.list.RequestListSearchResultsFactory$$anonfun$9$$anonfun$apply$1.apply$mcZ$sp(RequestListSearchResultsFactory.scala:176)
{code}

A possible consequence of this bug is that if a customer tries to go "My Requests" from the Customer Portal and selects "Closed requests" or "Any status", all the fields get grayed out and nothing happens. The only way to get the dropdown menus to work is to use the browser back-button.
h3. +Steps to reproduce+

The steps to reproduce this issue are currently unknown, as it is in theory not possible to delete the "Summary" field from the JIRA GUI. This issue might be occurring due to a direct database manipulation or the usage of a 3rd party add-on.
h3. +Workaround+

To verify if you are impacted by this bug, run the following query in the JIRA database (please replace XX with the ID next to "Uncaught exception thrown by REST service: key not found: " from the error message found in the log):
{code:java}
select * from "AO_54307E_VIEWPORTFIELD" where "FORM_ID" = XX;
{code}
If this query does not return any row, then it means that the request type that has the ID XX does not have any field.

To fix this issue:
 # Run the following query in the database to get the name of the invalid Request Type (please replace XX with the same value as the other query):
{code:java}
select "NAME" from "AO_54307E_VIEWPORTFORM" where "ID" = XX;
{code}

 # Open JIRA and look for this Request Type in the impacted Service Desk project by going to Project Settings > Request Types
 # Click on "Edit fields" next to "Internal IT"
 # Click on "Add a field", and choose the "Summary" field

